{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18641"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.09,0.09,0.06,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77797"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6907"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77797"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arcuate line (linea semicircularis) is an important anatomical landmark of the anterior abdominal wall where the arrangement of fascial layers changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical significance of the arcuate line?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Marks where external oblique aponeurosis ends","Junction where rectus abdominis originates","Site where transversus abdominis terminates","Location where linea alba begins","Point where posterior rectus sheath ends"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epoint where posterior rectus sheath ends\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the arcuate line. This occurs approximately halfway between the umbilicus and pubic symphysis. Above this line, the rectus abdominis muscle is enclosed within a fascial compartment formed by both anterior and posterior rectus sheaths. Below the arcuate line, only the anterior rectus sheath remains, with transversalis fascia lying directly posterior to the rectus muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarks where external oblique aponeurosis ends\u003C/strong\u003E - The external oblique aponeurosis continues below the arcuate line to form part of the anterior rectus sheath\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJunction where rectus abdominis originates\u003C/strong\u003E - The rectus abdominis muscle originates from the pubic crest and symphysis, not at the arcuate line\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESite where transversus abdominis terminates\u003C/strong\u003E - The transversus abdominis muscle continues below the arcuate line\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocation where linea alba begins\u003C/strong\u003E - The linea alba runs the entire length of the anterior abdominal wall from the xiphoid process to the pubic symphysis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the arcuate line is clinically relevant for surgical approaches to the anterior abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The arcuate line marks the point where the posterior rectus sheath ends, approximately halfway between the umbilicus and pubic symphysis.","Above the arcuate line, the rectus abdominis muscle is enclosed by both anterior and posterior rectus sheaths.","Below the arcuate line, only the anterior rectus sheath remains, with transversalis fascia lying posterior to the rectus muscle."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:49:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T10:50:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77797"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"